{{otherpeople|Timothy Walker}}

'''Timothy Walker''' (December 1, 1806 <U+2013> January 15, 1856) was an American lawyer who founded the [[Cincinnati Law School]] and was its first Dean.

==Biography== 
Timothy Walker was born in [[Wilmington, Massachusetts]], [[USA]], and graduated from [[Harvard University|Harvard]] in 1826. From 1826 to 1829 he taught mathematics, and he studied law at [[Harvard Law School]] 1829 and 1830. In 1831 he moved to [[Cincinnati, Ohio]], where he was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] and started a practice.<ref name=apple>[http://virtualology.com/aptimothywalker1/ Timothy Walker] [[Appletons' Cyclop<U+00E6>dia of American Biography]],</ref>

In 1833, Walker, along with [[Edward King (Ohio politician)|Edward King]] and [[John C. Wright (politician)|John C. Wright]], founded the [[Cincinnati Law School]], the first law school in the West. Walker served as Dean, and continued in that position when the school merged with [[Cincinnati College]] in 1835. He was Dean 1833 to 1844.<ref name=UCCOLhist>[http://www.law.uc.edu/about-us/history History of UC College of Law].</ref>

Walker was President Judge of the [[Hamilton County, Ohio|Hamilton County]] [[Ohio Courts of Common Pleas|Court of Common Pleas]], founded the ''Western Law Journal'' in 1843, and was its editor. His ''Introduction to American Law'' (1837, revised several times) was for many years "the most generally used text-book in the country".<ref name=cent>{{cite book |title=Centennial history of Cincinnati and representative citizens |volume=1 |first=Charles Theodore |last=Greve |page=630 |publisher=Biographical Publishing Company |location=Chicago |year=1904 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=eJxABLtxX60C&pg=PA630}}</ref> This book earned him the title "The American [[William Blackstone|Blackstone]]".<ref name=UCCOLhist/> Walker wrote a number of other historical and legal books.<ref name=apple/> He was given the degree LL.D. by Harvard in 1854, and was the Phi Beta Kappa orator at that institution in 1850.<ref name=cent/>

Timothy Walker died in Cincinnati in 1856.<ref name=cent/>

